         <change when="2011-09-07T15:47:39.768-04:00"
                 who="http://papyri.info/editor/users/simoeis">In this dated letter from Lucius Bellenus Gemellus to his son Sabinus, Gemellus asks for, among other things, food items to be sent for a festival of Harpocrates (for discussion of this festival, see F. Perpillou-Thomas,  _Fêtes d'Egypte ptolémaïque et romaine d'après la documentation papyrologique grecque_ (Leuven 1993), 88-89).  Gemellus states in line 12 that the festival will take place on the 14th, but in lines 28 to 29 of the ed. pr. we find that the papyrus is dated (ἔτους) ια Τραιανοῦ Καίσαρος το[ῦ κ]υρίου, [Τ]ῦβι, ιθ̣, which raises the following question: if the letter was written on the 19th of Tybi, how was it that the festival was planned for the 14th?  Does he mean that it will be on the 14th of the following month, Mechir?  If Mechir is indeed meant, the omission of any reference to it is odd.  Perpillou-Thomas noticed this discrepancy (see BL X, 67) and suggested that the 11th or 12th of Tybi was probably the intended date of the letter.  This suspicion is correct and can be confirmed by consulting a photograph of the original, which is made available by the University of Pennsylvania (accessible via HGV).  Here we see that Gemellus in fact wrote the letter two days before the festival, on Tybi 12 (ιβ) (= January 8).  (For parallel forms of the beta in ιβ, see [Τ]ῦβι in line 29 and Σαβίνωι in line 2).   &#xD;
&#xD;
I have made the necessary change to the Duke text.  The correct date is already in HGV.  Only now the statement "Tag unsicher" should be removed.&#xD;
</change>
